Here's the complete migration to ASP.NET Core (.NET 8):

## Pattern Classification

| Original Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | ASP.NET request termination | Remove — just return from action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Redirect + Thread.Abort | Return `Redirect(url)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow via exception | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // WebForms event handlers become MVC action methods
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Response.Clear(), AddHeader(), Write(), End() all replaced
        // by returning a FileResult. ASP.NET Core handles headers
        // and content automatically — no Thread.Abort involved.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Response.Redirect("/login", true) called Thread.Abort to
            // stop execution after the redirect header was set.
            // In ASP.NET Core, returning Redirect() naturally ends the
            // action — no abort needed.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch block REMOVED — it existed only
        // because Response.Redirect(url, true) threw it internally.
        // ASP.NET Core redirects never throw.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Writing to Response body then returning a result** | Don't mix `Response.Body.WriteAsync()` with `return File(...)`. Pick one. Use `IActionResult` return values. |
| **`Response.Redirect()` doesn't stop execution** | In Framework, `true` meant "abort the thread now." In Core, `Redirect()` just sets headers — code **continues** executing. Always `return` it. |
| **Null reference on `User.Identity`** | `User.Identity` can be `null` in Core if no auth middleware is configured. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or the `[Authorize]` attribute. |
| **Missing `ThreadAbortException`** | The type doesn't exist meaningfully in .NET 8. Catch blocks referencing it won't compile if they also call `ResetAbort`. Remove them. |
| **`Response.End()` doesn't exist** | No equivalent in Core. Return from the action method — the framework handles flushing and closing the response. |

## If you have long-running export work

Use `HttpContext.RequestAborted` for cooperative cancellation:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> ExportLarge(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds HttpContext.RequestAborted
    // to this parameter. If the client disconnects, the token fires.
    var data = await GenerateLargeReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(data, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

The fundamental shift: Framework used **preemptive** termination (`Thread.Abort` injecting an exception). Core uses **cooperative** cancellation — your code must check the `CancellationToken` voluntarily. Returning an `IActionResult` naturally ends the request with no abort needed.
